==Consonants==
{| border="1" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="4" class="wikitable" !Letter ![[w:International Phonetic Alphabet|IPA]] !Example (IPA) !Example (Written) !Meaning !Notes |- |'''m''' |{{IPA|m}} |{{IPA|ujiːse}} |''u'''m'''a'''m'''a'' |"my/our mother" |Pronounced as in English. |- |'''n''' |{{IPA|n}} |{{IPA|uniːna}} |''u'''n'''i'''n'''a'' |"his/her/their mother" | Pronounced as in '''''n'''o'' in English. |- |'''ny''' |{{IPA|ɲ}} |{{IPA|iːɲɔːni}} |''i'''ny'''oni'' |"bird" | Pronounced as in vi'''gn'''ette. |- |'''ng''' |{{IPA|ŋ}} |{{IPA|iːŋɔane}} |''i'''ng'''ane'' |"child" | Pronounced as in ''fi'''ng'''er''. |- |'''p''' |{{IPA|p}} |{{IPA|iːpiːpi}} |''i'''p'''i'''p'''i'' |"pipe for smoking" | This consonant is pronounced somewhat as in ''s'''p'''eech''. |- |'''ph''' |{{IPA|pʰ}} |{{IPA|pʰɛːɠa}} |''-'''ph'''eka'' |"cook" | Pronounced as in '''''p'''in'' never as in ''phone'' |- |'''t''' |{{IPA|t}} |{{IPA|iːtiːje}} |''i'''t'''iye'' |"tea" | Pronounced somewhat as in English. |- |'''th''' |{{IPA|tʰ}} |{{IPA|tʰaːtʰa}} |''-'''th'''a'''th'''a'' |"take" | Pronounced somewhat as in English but more fully [[w:Aspiration (phonetics)|aspirated]] i.e. with more air escaping from the mouth. |- |'''k''' |{{IPA|k}} |{{IPA|umakɔːti}} |''uma'''k'''oti'' |"bride" | Pronounced somewhat as in English. |- | |{{IPA|ɠ}} |{{IPA|uɠuza}} |''u'''k'''uza'' |"to come" | Pronounced somewhere between k and g in English. |- |'''kh''' |{{IPA|kʰ}} |{{IPA|iːkʰaːnda}} |''i'''kh'''anda'' |"head" | Pronounced somewhat like c in '''''c'''at'' but more aspirated. |- |'''g''' |{{IPA|g}} |{{IPA|ugɔgɔ}} |''u'''g'''o'''g'''o'' |"granny" | Pronounced somewhat like in '''''g'''o'' never as in gem. |- |'''b''' |{{IPA|ɓ}} |{{IPA|ubaːba}} |''u'''b'''a'''b'''a'' |"my/our father" | Pronounced with [[w:Implosive consonant|implosion]]; the movement of the muscles approaches more or less that when smoking a pipe. |- |'''bh''' |{{IPA|b}} |{{IPA|bala}} |''-'''bh'''ala'' |"write" | Pronounced more or less as in English '''''b'''ed''. |- |'''d''' |{{IPA|d}} |{{IPA|iːdaːda}} |''i'''d'''a'''d'''a'' |"duck" | Pronounced more or less as in English '''''d'''uck''. |- |'''f''' |{{IPA|f}} |{{IPA|iːfu}} |''i'''f'''u'' |"cloud" | Pronounced more or less as in English '''''f'''un''. |- |'''v''' |{{IPA|v}} |{{IPA|vaːla}} |''-'''v'''ala'' |"close" | Pronounced as in English '''''v'''an''. |- |'''s''' |{{IPA|s}} |{{IPA|iːsiːsu}} |''i'''s'''i'''s'''u'' |"stomach" | Pronounced as in English '''''s'''ay''. |- |'''sh''' |{{IPA|ʃ}} |{{IPA|iːʃuːmi}} |''i'''sh'''umi' |"ten" | Pronounced as in English '''''sh'''all''. |- |'''h''' |{{IPA|h}} |{{IPA|haːmba}} |''-'''h'''amba' |"go" | Pronounced as in English '''''h'''and''. |- | |{{IPA|ɦ}} |{{IPA|iːɦaːʃi}} |''i'''h'''ashi' |"horse" | Pronounced as in English ''be'''h'''ind''. |- |'''l''' |{{IPA|l}} |{{IPA|lala}} |''-'''l'''a'''l'''a' |"sleep" | Pronounced as in English '''''l'''augh''. |- |'''hl''' |{{IPA|ɬ}} |{{IPA|ɬaːla}} |''-'''hl'''ala' |"sit" | Pronounced as in Welsh ''Llanelli''. An approximation is pronouncing l and h simultaneously. |- |'''dl''' |{{IPA|ɮ}} |{{IPA|ɮaːla}} |''-'''dl'''a' |"eat" | This consonant is [[w:Voiced_(phonetics)|voiced]] form of hl. This means the vocal cords are vibrating during articulation. |- |'''tsh''' |{{IPA|tʃ}} |{{IPA|utʃaːni}} |''u'''tsh'''ani' |"grass" | Pronounced as the English '''''ch'''in''. |- |'''j''' |{{IPA|ʤ}} |{{IPA|uʤu}} |''u'''j'''u' |"honey" | This consonant is pronounced as the English '''''j'''ump''. |- |'''kl''' |{{IPA|kɬ'}} (*) |{{IPA|kɬ'aːja}} |''-'''kl'''aya' |"split" | To produced this sound: # Raise the back of the tongue against the soft palate. # Keep the front part of the tongue down behind the lower teeth. # Force air through the closure caused by raising the back of the tongue against the soft palate. |}
(*) IPA transcription by G. Poulos & C.T. Msimang. ''A linguistic aalysis of Zulu.'' Cape Town: Via Afrika, 1998.
==Clicks== {| border="1" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="4" class="wikitable" !Letter ![[w:International Phonetic Alphabet|IPA]] !Example (IPA) !Example (Written) !Meaning !Notes |- |'''c''' |{{IPA|ǀ}} |{{IPA|ǀela}} |''-'''c'''ela'' |''request'' | To produced this sound: # Place the tip of the tongue against the upper front teeth and gum. # Depress the centre of the tongue. # Release the tip of the tongue drawing it slightly backwards. |- |'''q''' |{{IPA|ǃ}} |{{IPA|ǃala}} |''-'''q'''ala'' |''request'' | To produced this sound: # Press the upper part of the tongue-tip against the part between the teeth ridge and the hard palate. # Raise the back of the tongue so that it touches the soft palate. # Depress the centre of the tongue. # Release sharply downwards the tip of the tongue. |- |'''x''' |{{IPA|ǁ}} |{{IPA|ǁɔːǁɔː}} |''-'''x'''o'''x'''o'' |''chat, converse'' | To produced this sound: # Place the upper part of the tongue-tip against the part between the teeth ridge and the hard palate. # Raise the back of the tongue towards the soft palate. # Withdraw one side of the tongue from the upper teeth. |}
Note: c is often described as the sound in ''tut-tut'' while x is the sound used for encouraging horses.
The click sounds can be aspirated, [[w:Nasal consonant|nasalised]], voiced or voiced and nasalised together. This is shown in the below table.
{| border="1" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="4" class="wikitable" !Aspirated !Nasalised !Voiced !Voiced and Nasalised |- | ch | nc | gc | ngc |- | qh | nq | gq | ngq |- | xh | nx | gx | ngx |}
[[Category:Zulu]]

{{Microprocessor Design}}

'''Exceptions''', are situations where the processor needs to stop executing the current code because of an error. In these cases, the processor typically begins running an '''exception handling routine''' to resolve the error, and then returns to the normal program flow. For instance, if the ALU attempts to divide by zero, or if an addition causes overflow, an exception might be triggered. The processor needs to stop operation and fix the error before the program can be resumed.

Some common examples of exceptions are arithmetic overflow or underflow, division by zero, or attempting to access a memory location that does not exist.

{{Microprocessor Design}}
Taking the idea of superscalar operations to the next level, it is possible (and frequently desirable) to put multiple microprocessor cores onto a single chip, and have the cores operate in parallel with one another.
== Symmetric Multi-core ==
A symmetric multi-core processor is one that has multiple cores on a single chip, and all of those cores are identical.
{{TextBox|'''Example: Intel Core 2''':
The Intel Core 2 is an example of a symmetric multi-core processor. The Core 2 can have either 2 cores on chip ("Core 2 Duo") or 4 cores on chip ("Core 2 Quad"). Each core in the Core 2 chip is symmetrical, and can function independently of one another. It requires a mixture of scheduling software and hardware to farm tasks out to each core.}}
{{TextBox|'''Example: Parallax Propeller''':
The Parallax Propeller is an example of a symmetric multi-core processor. The Parallax Propeller has 8 cores on chip, each one a 32-bit RISC processor. Each core in the Parallax Propeller chip is symmetrical, and can function independently of one another.}}
== Asymmetric Multi-core ==
An asymmetric multi-core processor is one that has multiple cores on a single chip, but those cores might be different designs. For instance, there could be 2 general purpose cores and 2 vector cores on a single chip.
{{TextBox|'''Example: Cell Processor'''
IBM's Cell processor, used in the Sony PlayStation 3 video game console is an asymmetrical multi-core processor. The Cell has 9 processor cores on board, one general purpose processor, and 8 data-processing cores. The one multipurpose core, known as the '''Power Processor Element''' (PPE) controls the communication between the other cores, and distributes computing tasks to the other cores for processing. The other 8 cores are known as '''Synergistic Processor Elements''' (SPE), and are specially designed to have high floating-point throughput, especially with vector operations.}}
{{TextBox|'''Example: Kilocore'''
Rapport's Kilocore processor, is an asymmetrical multi-core processor. The Kilocore has one general purpose processor, a PowerPC processing core, and either 256 or 1024 data processing cores on-chip. The cores are designed to run at extremely low power, so the overall chip is faster and yet uses less power than typical desktop CPUs<ref>[http://www.tomshardware.com/news/ibm-rapport-kilocore,2575.html Tom's hardware: "IBM says Kilocore technology will outrun today's mobile processors"] 2006</ref>.}}
== Symmetric Multicore ==
[[Image:IntelCore2DuoE6600.jpg|thumb|right|The Intel Core 2 Duo]]
A symmetric multi-core processor is a processor which has multiple cores that are all exactly the same. Every single core has the same architecture and the same capabilities. An example of a symmetric multi-core system is the Intel Core 2 Duo processor.
Each core has the same capabilities, so it requires that there is an arbitration unit to give each core a specific task. Software that uses techniques like '''multithreading''' makes the best use of a multi-core processor like the Intel Core 2.
{{-}}
== Asymmetric Multi-core ==
In an asymmetric multi-core processor, the chip has multiple cores on-board, but the cores might be different designs. Each core will have different capabilities.
=== Example: IBM Cell Processor ===
An example of an asymmetric multi-core processor is the IBM Cell processor.
{| class="wikitable" width=100% |- |[[Image:SPE (cell).png|300px|center]] |[[Image:PPE (Cell).png|300px|center]] |- |colspan=2|Block diagrams of the IBM Cell processor. The Cell processor has 8 SPE cores (left) and 1 PPE core (right). The PPE core is the primary core, and controls the behavior of the SPE cores. |}
The IBM Cell processor has 1 PPE that controls the chip, and 8 SPEs that are designed for high mathematical throughput. The IBM Cell processor is designed as follows:
[[Image:IBM Cell Block Diagram.svg|center|400px]]
Notice how the SPE cores only connect to the PPE, and not to each other. Notice also that the PPE core is much larger then the individual SPE cores.
