__FORCETOC__ ==If== <tt>If</tt>, '''PRGM:CTL:1''', requires a criteria argument (condition) to be stated immediately afterwards which will allow the program to determine whether the following instructions are to be executed. The argument or arguments (which will be referred to as a condition) is a boolean result, meaning that they will be true (non-zero, ie 1) or false (zero, ie 0). For more help on booleans, see the Boolean Reference (somewhere not yet).
A simple If is used when the programmer wishes to test for a condition, then execute '''one''' instruction (following the if statement) if the condition returns true.
===Syntax: If=== {{bcode:Syntax| :If ''condition'' :''statement'' }} *where ''condition'' is any statement resulting in a zero or non zero result **if ''condition'' returns true (again, non-zero), ''statement'' is executed **if ''condition'' returns false (zero) ''statement'' is not executed
===Ex: If=== The following example demonstrates a very basic If statement that will display "x > Five": {{bcode:Example| :6&rarr;X :If X>5 :Disp "X > FIVE!" }} It will display "x > Five" because the condition x>5 (6 is greater than 5) returns true. If x had been 3, condition would return false (3 is not greater than 5),and nothing would display.
===Ex: If One=== The following program will always display "Hello World" because the condition 1 will always return 1 (which is non-zero) and therefore the condition is always true {{bcode:Example| :If 1 :Disp "Hello World" }} and likewise the following will never display "Goodbye" because it always returns 0 {{bcode:Example| :If 0 :Disp "Goodbye World" }}
==If Then End (If Then)== <tt>If</tt> '''PRGM:CTL:1''' <tt>Then</tt> '''PRGM:CTL:2''' <tt>End</tt> '''PRGM:CTL:7''' conditional statements (more commonly known as <tt>If Then</tt> statements) are used when more than one statement must be executed if a condition returns true. It is very much like the simple <tt>If</tt> statement, with the obvious difference that multiple statments are executed instead of one. ===Syntax If Then=== The <tt>If</tt> statement requires a condition, then a <tt>Then</tt> command must follow on the next line, followed by one or more statements which will execute if the condition returns true. The <tt>If</tt> block is ended by a <tt>End</tt> statement which tells the calculator that all following statments are to be executed as normal. {{bcode:Syntax| :If ''condition'' :Then :''statement1'' :''statement2'' :''statementn'' :End }} *Where condition is any statement resulting in a true or false result. **if condition returns true, statement1, statement2... statementn (all statements between Then and End) will execute **if condition returns false, the statements between Then and End are not executed, and the program continues with the first statement after End
===Ex: If Then=== {{bcode:Example| :If x<u>></u>5 :Then :Disp x :x+1&rarr;x :Disp x :End }}
{{bcode:Output| 6 7 }} if x = 6, but would display nothing if x was less than five
==If Then Else End== <tt>If</tt> '''PRGM:CTL:1''' <tt>Then</tt> '''PRGM:CTL:2''' <tt>Else</tt> '''PRGM:CTL:3''' <tt>End</tt> '''PRGM:CTL:7''' If elses are used when the programmer needs to make a choice where if the condition returns non-zero, statements are executed, but if the condition returns zero, other statements are executed. Either way, only one set of instructions are executed ===Syntax: Else If=== {{bcode:Syntax| :If ''condition'' :Then :''trueStatements'' :Else :''falseStatments'' :End }} *Where condition is any statement resulting in a zero or non zero result. **if condition returns nonzero, trueStatments (insructions between Then and Else) will execute, then the instruction after End is executed **if condition returns zero, falseStatements (instructions between Else and End) are executed, then the instruction after End is executed
===Ex: Else If=== {{bcode:Example| :If X<u>></u>5 :Then :Disp "Hello World I'm" :Disp "Big like five" :Else :Disp "Goodbye World" :Disp "I'm small like four" :End }} Would display {{bcode:Output| Hello World I'm Big like Five }} if X were greater than or equal to five, but would display the following if X were less than five {{bcode:Output| Goodbye World I'm small like four }}
===Syntax: While=== <tt>While</tt> loop executes a block of commands between the While and End commands as long as the specified condition is true. The condition is tested at the beginning of the loop (when the End command is encountered), so if the condition is initially false, the block of commands will never get executed. {{bcode:Syntax| :While ''condition is true'' :''statement'' :End }} *where ''condition'' is any statement resulting in a zero or non zero result **if ''condition'' returns true (again, non-zero), ''statement'' continues to execute **if ''condition'' returns false (zero) ''statement'' stops execution
===Ex: While=== The following example demonstrates a very basic While Loop that will display x until y is not true: {{bcode:Example| :While y≠0 :Disp X :End }}
{{BottomNav|Advanced Variables|GetKey}}

This section of the Spanish wikibook discusses the Spanish past tense. You have presumably learned about the present tense, therefore this section assumes a knowledge of said tense and previously learned vocabulary.
='''''La formación del pretérito'''''=
The preterite is used to speak of an event that happened at a specific time (I went to Sallly's (yesterday)). First, we must learn the preterite tense, is used for past actions that are seen as completed. There are two different forms of the preterite, one for -ar verbs and a seperate form for -er and -ir verbs.
'''''1. Los verbos regulares del preterito - ar'''''
Let us learn the conjugation for regular -ar verbs in the preterite now. For example:
; El preterito - ejemplos de los verbos ''-ar'' {| style="background:#bbeebb" ! colspan="3" | cantar (to sing) |- | | style="background:#ffffff" | '''Singular''' | style="background:#ffffff" | '''Plural''' |- | style="background:#ffffff" | '''First''' | style="background:#ffffff" | cant'''é''' | style="background:#ffffff" | cant'''amos''' |- | style="background:#ffffff" | '''Second''' | style="background:#ffffff" | cant'''aste''' | style="background:#ffffff" | cant'''asteis''' |- | style="background:#ffffff" | '''Third''' | style="background:#ffffff" | cant'''ó''' | style="background:#ffffff" | cant'''aron''' |}
{| style="background:#bbeebb" ! colspan="3" | nadar (to swim) |- | | style="background:#ffffff" | '''Singular''' | style="background:#ffffff" | '''Plural''' |- | style="background:#ffffff" | '''First''' | style="background:#ffffff" | nad'''é''' | style="background:#ffffff" | nad'''amos''' |- | style="background:#ffffff" | '''Second''' | style="background:#ffffff" | nad'''aste''' | style="background:#ffffff" | nad'''asteis''' |- | style="background:#ffffff" | '''Third''' | style="background:#ffffff" | nad'''ó''' | style="background:#ffffff" | nad'''aron''' |}
Notice the pattern: in each form, you must drop the "ar" in the infinitive form. For the first person singular, you add "é", for the second person singular you add "aste", for the third it is "aron". As for plural, in the first person "amos" is added, in the second "asteis", and in the third we add "aron".
On to the exercises...
'''''2. Los verbos regulares del preterito - er y ir'''''
Now, we will learn the conjugation for regular -er and -ir verbs. For example:
; El preterito - ejemplos de los verbos ''-er'' y ''-ir'' {| style="background:#bbeebb" ! colspan="3" | beber (to drink) |- | | style="background:#ffffff" | '''Singular''' | style="background:#ffffff" | '''Plural''' |- | style="background:#ffffff" | '''First''' | style="background:#ffffff" | beb'''í''' | style="background:#ffffff" | beb'''imos''' |- | style="background:#ffffff" | '''Second''' | style="background:#ffffff" | beb'''iste''' | style="background:#ffffff" | beb'''isteis''' |- | style="background:#ffffff" | '''Third''' | style="background:#ffffff" | beb'''ió''' | style="background:#ffffff" | beb'''ieron''' |}
{| style="background:#bbeebb" ! colspan="3" | vivir (to live) |- | | style="background:#ffffff" | '''Singular''' | style="background:#ffffff" | '''Plural''' |- | style="background:#ffffff" | '''First''' | style="background:#ffffff" | viv'''í''' | style="background:#ffffff" | viv'''imos''' |- | style="background:#ffffff" | '''Second''' | style="background:#ffffff" | viv'''iste''' | style="background:#ffffff" | viv'''isteis''' |- | style="background:#ffffff" | '''Third''' | style="background:#ffffff" | viv'''ió''' | style="background:#ffffff" | viv'''ieron'''
|}
Notice the pattern: in each form, you must drop the "er" or "ir" in the infinitive form. For the first person singular, you add "í", for the second person singular you add "iste", for the third it is "ieron". As for plural, in the first person "imos" is added, in the second "isteis", and in the third we add "ieron".
On to the exercises...
'''''3. Los verbos con cambios de deletreo en la forma "yo" - 'car', 'gar', 'zar''''''
There are also verbs that have a spelling change in the first person singular form. These changes occur in verbs that end in "car", "gar", or "zar" and, in the first two cases, are necessary in order to maintain the original sound of the written verb (in speaking, we tend to pronounce the word correctly without having to think about it).
As explained in the "Alfabeto" section, both "c" and "g" have a 'hard' sound before an "a", "o" or "u", and a soft sound before "e" and "i". In the first-person Preterite, then, the "é" ending would change the 'k/' sound of the "c" to an 's/' sound, and the hard-g sound to a 'h/' sound. In order to maintain the original sound of the verb, we change the spelling. For a "-car" verb, we change the "c" to a "qu" when it comes before "é":
{| style="background:#bbeebb" ! colspan="3" | practi''car'' (to practice) |- | | style="background:#ffffff" | '''Singular''' | style="background:#ffffff" | '''Plural''' |- | style="background:#ffffff" | '''First''' | style="background:#ffffff" | practi'''qué''' | style="background:#ffffff" | practic'''amos''' |- | style="background:#ffffff" | '''Second''' | style="background:#ffffff" | practic'''aste''' | style="background:#ffffff" | practic'''asteis''' |- | style="background:#ffffff" | '''Third''' | style="background:#ffffff" | practic'''ó''' | style="background:#ffffff" | practic'''aron''' |}
Similarly, for a "-gar" verb, we add a "u" after the "g":
{| style="background:#bbeebb" ! colspan="3" | lle''gar'' (to arrive) |- | | style="background:#ffffff" | '''Singular''' | style="background:#ffffff" | '''Plural''' |- | style="background:#ffffff" | '''First''' | style="background:#ffffff" | lle'''gué''' | style="background:#ffffff" | lleg'''amos''' |- | style="background:#ffffff" | '''Second''' | style="background:#ffffff" | lleg'''aste''' | style="background:#ffffff" | lleg'''asteis''' |- | style="background:#ffffff" | '''Third''' | style="background:#ffffff" | lleg'''ó''' | style="background:#ffffff" | lleg'''aron''' |}
For "-zar" verbs, there is no longer a change in pronunciation, but tradition calls for the letter "z" to be followed only by "a", "o" or "u". With a following "e" or "i", we change the "z" to a "c":
{| style="background:#bbeebb" ! colspan="3" | comen''zar'' (to begin) |- | | style="background:#ffffff" | '''Singular''' | style="background:#ffffff" | '''Plural''' |- | style="background:#ffffff" | '''First''' | style="background:#ffffff" | comen'''cé''' | style="background:#ffffff" | comenz'''amos''' |- | style="background:#ffffff" | '''Second''' | style="background:#ffffff" | comenz'''aste''' | style="background:#ffffff" | comenz'''asteis''' |- | style="background:#ffffff" | '''Third''' | style="background:#ffffff" | comenz'''ó''' | style="background:#ffffff" | comenz'''aron''' |}
On to the exercises...
'''''Ejercicios del pretérito'''''
These exercises take what we have learned so far and integrate everything together. Be familiar with the first three sections of el tiempo pasado.
On to the exercises...
='''''La formación del imperfecto'''''=
The imperfect tense is used to refer to actions in the past that occurred repeatedly. E.g. I used to play with dolls. These have an indefinite time. It's often used to describe past behaviours and likes, especially of childhood.
'''''1. La formacion del imperfecto - los verbos ar'''''
Just as with the preterite, in the imperfect construction -ar verbs receive their own conjugation. For example:
; El preterito - ejemplos de los verbos ''-ar'' {| style="background:#bbeebb" ! colspan="3" | hablar (to speak) |- | | style="background:#ffffff" | '''Singular''' | style="background:#ffffff" | '''Plural''' |- | style="background:#ffffff" | '''First''' | style="background:#ffffff" | habl'''aba''' | style="background:#ffffff" | habl'''ábamos''' |- | style="background:#ffffff" | '''Second''' | style="background:#ffffff" | habl'''abas''' | style="background:#ffffff" | habl'''abais''' |- | style="background:#ffffff" | '''Third''' | style="background:#ffffff" | habl'''aba''' | style="background:#ffffff" | habl'''aban''' |}
{| style="background:#bbeebb" ! colspan="3" | cantar (to sing) |- | | style="background:#ffffff" | '''Singular''' | style="background:#ffffff" | '''Plural''' |- | style="background:#ffffff" | '''First''' | style="background:#ffffff" | cant'''aba''' | style="background:#ffffff" | cant'''ábamos''' |- | style="background:#ffffff" | '''Second''' | style="background:#ffffff" | cant'''abas''' | style="background:#ffffff" | cant'''abais''' |- | style="background:#ffffff" | '''Third''' | style="background:#ffffff" | cant'''aba''' | style="background:#ffffff" | cant'''aban''' |}
Notice the pattern: in the imperfect construction we drop the "ar" and add our endings. As for the singular, in the first person we add "aba", in the second person we add "abas", and in the third person we add "aba". In the plural, for the first person we add "ábamos" (with an accent), for the second person we add "abais", and in the third we add "aban".
Onto the exercises...
'''''2. La formacion del imperfecto - los verbos er y ir'''''
Just as in the preterite, the -er and -ir verbs have their own conjugation. For example:
; El preterito - ejemplos de los verbos ''-er'' y ''-ir'' {| style="background:#bbeebb" ! colspan="3" | correr (to run) |- | | style="background:#ffffff" | '''Singular''' | style="background:#ffffff" | '''Plural''' |- | style="background:#ffffff" | '''First''' | style="background:#ffffff" | corr'''ía''' | style="background:#ffffff" | corr'''íamos''' |- | style="background:#ffffff" | '''Second''' | style="background:#ffffff" | corr'''ías''' | style="background:#ffffff" | corr'''íais''' |- | style="background:#ffffff" | '''Third''' | style="background:#ffffff" | corr'''ía''' | style="background:#ffffff" | corr'''ían''' |}
{| style="background:#bbeebb" ! colspan="3" | asistir (to attend) |- | | style="background:#ffffff" | '''Singular''' | style="background:#ffffff" | '''Plural''' |- | style="background:#ffffff" | '''First''' | style="background:#ffffff" | asist'''ía''' | style="background:#ffffff" | asist'''íamos''' |- | style="background:#ffffff" | '''Second''' | style="background:#ffffff" | asist'''ías''' | style="background:#ffffff" | asist'''íais''' |- | style="background:#ffffff" | '''Third''' | style="background:#ffffff" | asist'''ía''' | style="background:#ffffff" | asist'''ían''' |}
Notice the pattern: in the imperfect construction we drop the "er" or "ir" and add our endings. As for the singular, in the first person we add "ía", in the second person we add "ías", and in the third person we add "ía". In the plural, for the first person we add "íamos" (with an accent), for the second person we add "íais", and in the third we add "ían".
Onto the exercises...
'''''3. Los verbos irregulares en la forma de imperfecto: 'ser', 'ir', y 'ver''''''
Only three verbs are irregular in the imperfect construction: ''ser'', ''ir'', and ''ver'':
{| style="background:#bbeebb" ! colspan="3" | ser (to be) |- | | style="background:#ffffff" | '''Singular''' | style="background:#ffffff" | '''Plural''' |- | style="background:#ffffff" | '''First''' | style="background:#ffffff" | era | style="background:#ffffff" | éramos |- | style="background:#ffffff" | '''Second''' | style="background:#ffffff" | eras | style="background:#ffffff" | erais |- | style="background:#ffffff" | '''Third''' | style="background:#ffffff" | era | style="background:#ffffff" | eran |}
