The three Hesperides were sisters who guarded the Garden of the Hesperides, aptly named.  They were the daughters of Atlas.

The garden was a gift of Mother Earth to Hera on her wedding day.  In this garden, which only immortals could reach, were the Golden Apples.  One of Herakles' twelve labors was to retrieve these apples, but, being mortal, he could not.  He convinced Atlas to do so for him.

{{BookCat}}

The three Hesperides were sisters who guarded the Garden of the Hesperides, aptly named. They were the daughters of Atlas.

The garden was a gift of Mother Earth to Hera on her wedding day. In this garden, which only immortals could reach, were the Golden Apples. One of Hercules' twelve labors was to retrieve these apples, but, being mortal, he could not. He convinced Atlas to do so for him.

{{BookCat}}

The Seasons, or the Horae, were both the personifications of the seasons, but were also the guardians of the cloudy entrance to Mount Olympus, as well as remembering which gods/goddesses were on Mount Olympus and which were abroad.

There were only three Seasons because classically, only spring, summer and winter were recognized.

{{BookCat}}

Life and Death refers to situations that one would get themselves into but have a bleak ending.  Or do they? There is a reason that it is called "''Life and'' Death" and not just "Death".  Making good things out of life and death situations are key features in playing Go.  The ability to make eyes and the ability to escape to neighboring units of stones are all key things to learn when you study Go and in particularly life and death problems.  For more info, check out the [[../Resources/]] page.

